The following image shows the 'dut' netlist and how the cells are distributed between submodules.
![dut](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/89401219/169650868-670f0022-806e-4828-a461-effc3a23fadd.png)

highlighted  red - part__0
highlighted  blue - part__1

The full test case files/scripts can be downloaded at [submod.zip](https://github.com/YosysHQ/yosys/files/8747624/submod.zip)


To reproduce:
`yosys run.ys`

For simulations described in 'Actual behavior' section
`./run_sim_original.sh`
`./run_sim_submode.sh`

Note you need iverilog for simulation.

## Expected behavior

*correct handling of the signal when individual bits of the signal are distributed between different submodules*

## Actual behavior

*The 'data' signal in both submodules is declared as 'inout' port. The data[2] is participating in the expression(~) which generates the 'out' signal in part__1, however the data[2] is not driven correctly - i.e. it is generated in the part__0 and isn't driven properly in part__1 *

The following images illustrate simulation result before creating submodules and after it respectively:

![sim_orig](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/89401219/169651381-a8b0a0e9-b6f7-4534-b0a2-5970e4b04c1b.png)
![sim_submod](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/89401219/169651388-a0e8b9ab-2b5c-4054-8c12-35dd4bdba3d8.png)

The second(fail) case shows the data[2] is 'z' in part__1 and it results in 'x' value on out[2] which is propagated further.

